
Target Temperature

Chef is preparing his restaurant's kitchen for the day.

There are NN stoves in the kitchen.
Initially, all the stoves have a temperature of 00.

Every minute, the following will happen:

    First, Chef can choose at most one stove and reset its temperature to 00 instantly.
    In particular, it is allowed to not reset the temperature of any stove, if Chef wishes to.
    Then, the temperature of every stove will increase by 11.

Note that it is allowed to reset the same stove multiple times (in different minutes).

Chef thinks the ii-th stove is ready when its temperature is exactly BiBi‚Äã.
Is it possible for Chef to make his choices in such a way that all NN stoves are ready simultaneously?
Input Format

    The first line of input will contain a single integer TT, denoting the number of test cases.
    Each test case consists of two lines of input.
        The first line of each test case contains a single integer NN.
        The second line contains NN space-separated integers B1,B2,‚Ä¶,BNB1‚Äã,B2‚Äã,‚Ä¶,BN‚Äã.

Output Format

For each test case, output on a new line the answer: Yes if it's possible for all NN stoves to be ready simultaneously, and No otherwise.

Each character of the output may be printed in either uppercase or lowercase, i.e. the strings NO, No, nO, and no will be treated as equivalent.
Constraints

    1‚â§T‚â§1051‚â§T‚â§105
    1‚â§N‚â§2‚ãÖ1051‚â§N‚â§2‚ãÖ105
    1‚â§Bi‚â§1091‚â§Bi‚Äã‚â§109
    The sum of NN over all test cases won't exceed 2‚ãÖ1052‚ãÖ105.

Sample 1:
Input
Output

3
2
1 3
3
4 4 4
4
5 6 6 5

Yes
Yes
No

Explanation:

Test case 11: One valid sequence of operations is as follows.

    Initially, the temperatures are [0,0][0,0].
    In the first minute, don't reset any stove. The temperatures are [1,1][1,1].
    In the second minute, again don't reset any stove. The temperatures are [2,2][2,2].
    In the third minute, reset the first stove, so the temperatures are [0,2][0,2].
    Then, every stove increases in temperature by 11, so the temperatures are [1,3][1,3].
    This is the desired final state.

Test case 22: Do nothing for four minutes and the temperatures are [4,4,4][4,4,4].

Test case 33: It can be shown that it's impossible to obtain the state [5,6,6,5][5,6,6,5] no matter what Chef does.

