Constrained Chopping

Alice and Bob are playing a game with an array AA of NN integers. The rules of the game are as follows:

    Let ‚à£A‚à£‚à£A‚à£ denote the current length of AA.
    If ‚à£A‚à£‚â§2‚à£A‚à£‚â§2, the game terminates immediately.
    Otherwise, Alice must choose an index ii such that 1<i<‚à£A‚à£1<i<‚à£A‚à£.
    Then, Bob must choose one of the following two actions:
        Delete all elements at indices 1,2,‚Ä¶,i1,2,‚Ä¶,i.
        Delete all elements at indices i,i+1,‚Ä¶,‚à£A‚à£i,i+1,‚Ä¶,‚à£A‚à£.
    After Bob's choice, the remaining elements are re-indexed starting from 11.

After the game terminates, Alice's score is defined to be the largest element remaining in the array.
Note that the game is only allowed to end when there are no more than two elements remaining in AA.

Alice wants to maximize her score, while Bob wants to minimize Alice's score.
Assuming both players play optimally, find Alice's final score.
Input Format

    The first line of input will contain a single integer TT, denoting the number of test cases.
    Each test case consists of two lines of input:
        The first line contains a single integer NN, denoting the initial size of the array.
        The second line contains NN space-separated integers A1,A2,‚Ä¶,ANA1‚Äã,A2‚Äã,‚Ä¶,AN‚Äã.

Output Format

For each test case, output on a new line a single integer representing Alice's score under optimal play.
Constraints

    1‚â§T‚â§1051‚â§T‚â§105
    1‚â§N‚â§2‚ãÖ1051‚â§N‚â§2‚ãÖ105
    1‚â§Ai‚â§N1‚â§Ai‚Äã‚â§N
    The sum of NN over all test cases does not exceed 2‚ãÖ1052‚ãÖ105.

Sample 1:
Input
Output

4
2
1 2
3
1 3 2
5
1 3 3 2 5
10
2 5 3 3 4 4 8 10 7 8

2
1
3
4

Explanation:

Test case 11: The array's length is already ‚â§2‚â§2, so no moves can be performed.
Alice's score is max‚Å°(1,2)=2max(1,2)=2.

Test case 22: Alice's only possible move is to choose i=2i=2.
Bob must then delete either [A1,A2][A1‚Äã,A2‚Äã] or [A2,A3][A2‚Äã,A3‚Äã].
He will choose to delete [A2,A3][A2‚Äã,A3‚Äã], leaving the array to be just [1][1]. Alice's score is hence 11.

Test case 33: Alice's optimal move is to choose i=3i=3.
Bob must now delete either the prefix [1,3,3][1,3,3] and leave [2,5][2,5] (giving Alice a score of max‚Å°(2,5)=5max(2,5)=5), or delete the suffix [3,2,5][3,2,5] and leave [1,3][1,3] (giving Alice a score of max‚Å°(1,3)=3max(1,3)=3).
Bob wants to minimize Alice's score, so he will choose the second option, leaving Alice with a score of 33.

It can be verified that Alice's other starting moves cannot attain a score larger than 33.

    If she chooses i=2i=2 on her first move, Bob will delete the suffix [3,3,2,5][3,3,2,5] leaving the array [1][1] with a score of 11.
    If she chooses i=4i=4 on her first move, Bob will delete the suffix [2,5][2,5] and make the array [1,3,3][1,3,3].
    Here, Alice is forced to choose the middle element, and Bob can delete [3,3][3,3] leaving Alice with a score of 11 again.

