Extended Viewing

After many years of work, Chef has managed to open an art gallery showcasing all his pieces.

There are NN pieces of art, arranged in a line from left to right.
The ii-th piece from the left has a beauty of AiAi‚Äã.
Each AiAi‚Äã equals either 11 or 22.

A famous art critic is visiting the gallery, and Chef knows that he will move through the gallery as follows.

Initially, the critic will start off by viewing the first art piece. Then, if pp denotes the index of the piece currently being viewed,

    If Ap=1Ap‚Äã=1, the critic will move to piece p+1p+1.
    If Ap=2Ap‚Äã=2, the critic will be absorbed in the beauty of what he just saw, and so will move to piece p+2p+2 without viewing piece p+1p+1.

More generally, starting from p=1p=1, after viewing piece pp the critic will move to piece p+App+Ap‚Äã.
If p+Ap>Np+Ap‚Äã>N, the critic will not view any more pieces.

For an arrangement of art pieces, let f(A)f(A) denote the number of them that the critic will view.

Chef wants f(A)f(A) to be as large as possible.
To achieve this, he can swap adjacent art pieces.
Functionally, this corresponds to choosing an index ii (1‚â§i<N1‚â§i<N) and performing swap(Ai,Ai+1)swap(Ai‚Äã,Ai+1‚Äã).

Your task is to find the minimum number of such adjacent swaps needed to attain the maximum possible value of f(A)f(A).
Input Format

    The first line of input will contain a single integer TT, denoting the number of test cases.
    Each test case consists of two lines of input.
        The first line of each test case contains a single integer NN.
        The second line contains NN space-separated integers A1,A2,‚Ä¶,ANA1‚Äã,A2‚Äã,‚Ä¶,AN‚Äã.

Output Format

For each test case, output on a new line the answer: the minimum number of adjacent swaps needed to maximize f(A)f(A).
Constraints

    1‚â§T‚â§1051‚â§T‚â§105
    1‚â§N‚â§2‚ãÖ1051‚â§N‚â§2‚ãÖ105
    1‚â§Ai‚â§21‚â§Ai‚Äã‚â§2
    The sum of NN over all test cases won't exceed 2‚ãÖ1052‚ãÖ105.

Sample 1:
Input
Output

4
3
2 1 2
4
2 2 2 2
5
1 2 1 2 1
10
2 1 1 2 1 2 1 2 2 1

0
0
1
4

Explanation:

Test case 11: With the given arrangement, the critic will behave as follows:

    Start at p=1p=1 and view the first piece.
    Then, because Ap=2Ap‚Äã=2, move to p+2=3p+2=3.
    View the piece at p=3p=3.
    Then, because Ap=2Ap‚Äã=2 and p+2>Np+2>N, no more pieces will be viewed.

So, f(A)=2f(A)=2 for the initial arrangement.
It can be shown that no matter what Chef does, it's impossible to make the critic view all 33 pieces. So, the maximum possible f(A)f(A) equals 22, and no swaps are needed.

Test case 22: All values of AiAi‚Äã are the same, so swapping cannot change anything.

Test case 33: The initial arrangement has f(A)=3f(A)=3, because the critic will view pieces 1,4,1,4, and 55.
However, if Chef swaps the last two pieces to obtain the arrangement [1,2,1,1,2][1,2,1,1,2], the critic will view pieces 1,2,4,51,2,4,5 which is better.
It's impossible for all 55 pieces to be viewed, so 44 is the best and one swap is needed to get there.


